text: Personally, I'm much more worried about the story than the casting. The cast seems great to me, (even though they took some liberties with the characters' races and ages). But from this trailer, this story essentially seems to be the exact same thing as the 2005 version. Fantastic Four + Doom go on a misson, it fails, they get powers, he's almost killed and becomes evil, they need to stop him  Yes, I know this is the origin from the comics, but that doesn't mean we need to see the origin story. Maybe do something different for a change. This just seems like The Amazing Spider-Man all over again, which was essentially a remake of the 2002 version, and it was only 10 years after original came out.

I know audiences were pretty negative to the original Fantastic 4, but those were movies that they grew accustomed to. They're not really going to be that interested in reliving the same movie experience in such a short amount of time after the original.  Then again maybe I'm wrong. text: This... This just looks terrible... Granted, I'm basing this OPINION purely on the trailer, but this just looks like the special kind of bad they have to try to do. I will honestly give it a fair shot, but based solely on the trailer, I'm not too hyped for it.  The Thing design looks awful, the story idea... what's the story idea? Send them to space, fight Doom? The original movie, which I'm not a big fan of but I'd take that over this, had a clear understanding of what it was. It was the corruption of Von Doom after the accident and his "friends", who were responsible for his corruption, standing up to him and fighting him down. They showed up how they controlled their abilities and how intelligent they were in doing so. They didn't have military backing. Heck, they had to fund the space exploration themselves.  This movie just puts me in mind of the Avengers, only the Avenger's effects looked better, in my opinion. It doesn't look like a good plot, doesn't look like any good acting and it looks entirely generic.

text: The preview alone goes so far away from the source material. I don't even know where to begin. They make them younger and instead of going into space, some alternate dimensional hop. Perhaps a younger audience can't relate to older people and a missing space program. Racebending is always a touchy subject. In the case of Nick Fury was a change for the better and he's awesome and it's been source material for years. Jordan is probably a good actor, but a change for the movie alone is just stupid and part of an annoying trend. At least they changed Franklin Storm so Johnny can't just be called a token, but it makes you wonder why they didn't touch Susan. Having Jordan play Thing would of just made more sense because it's easier to change characters who are not strictly connected with others. And as for thing, if Michael Chiklis hadn't already pulled off the look perfectly, this new one might be passible. It just looks overdone. Like some CG bakery nightmare. But if the actors can pull it off more power to them.  There's always those who enjoy creative liberty, but if they don't outnumber actual fans of the comics who immediately hate the changes, the movie will bomb big time. But then we'll get another reboot in 5-10 years anyway. The big hurdle will be getting past the origin story and doing well enough to make a sequel. Still doesn't look as bad as Dragonball Evolution or the 1994 Fantastic 4 film which was never officially released.
author: Dreydan

text: I can live with a black Johnny Storm, even though I see any radical changes to the characters or plotÂ Â as being disrespectful to the original artists. Are we saying that Jack Kirby drew him wrong, or Stan Lee wrote him wrong.  Â Anyway I am farÂ more concerned with that change they have made toÂ Mr Fantastic. Why have they changed him into a giftedÂ teenage science nerd. That was Peter Parker, not Reed Richards. Â  Richards was an accomplished, well respectedÂ scientist with grey hair. He was a man not a boy. Unless these changes are some new trendy Ultimate Universe thing, pandering to todays fickle teenagers.Â   Todays comics and movies should be faithful toÂ the history of the charactersÂ and respectÂ the writers and artistsÂ that made themÂ classics in the first place.

text: The problem with these fantastic four movies is that they treat them like single hero films, for example they make Reed the main character. What needs to be done with fantastic four is give every member an equal part making the team the main focus of the film and not one singular being. Another thing is do not stray too much from the source material, for example stop trying to shoe horn Doctor doom into the first film with some convoluted reason for his powers and metal face. Not one film has had doom with his armour and not superpowers and it baffles me why they avoid it. His origin is too complex to be summarised justly in just one film. Spanning his origin over the coarse of two films with only cameos in the first and in depth in the second would work well.  What makes fantastic four is the family dynamic and dysfunctional relationship they have. More focus has been put on unnecessary childish comedy and action in the movies previously made then this aspect and it hinders your relation to the characters and you do not care for their well being by the end as the characters just seem like cardboard cut outs and not as believable people in any real danger. So to summerise 1. more emphasis on the family relationship 2. give an equal character development for each character 3. if your gonna use doom don't try shoe horn him in with some bull shit superpower, just give him his Armour and technology 4. fantastic four has more then one villain, they have a large rooster to chose from(Molecule Man, Frightful Four, Super Skrull,   Annihilus etc) so pick one we haven't seen before. 5. Make it fun and light heart, yet serious and action packed. This can be done just look at the avengers or ant man. After all the team consists of a giant rock man and a man on fire who can fly. Don't take it too seriously.
